<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORE ON CONVENT AT DEATH CAMP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Being a survivor of Auschwitz-Birkenau, people often refer to me as the "lucky 
one." But, just how lucky was I? 
</P>
<P>
In December of 1944, the Nazis forced me to leave Auschwitz on a death march to 
escape the Soviet army which was rapidly approaching. But I left behind the 
ashes of my beloved mother and 14-year-old sister, who were murdered there with 
3 million other Jews. Their remains are scattered on the grounds of Auschwitz, 
the largest Jewish burial ground in all the world. 
</P>
<P>
Two years ago I finally mustered the courage to return to this holy cemetery. I 
was stunned to see a Catholic convent on these sacred grounds, so saturated 
with Jewish blood. 
</P>
<P>
I realized that the presence of the nuns here was the beginning of the final 
revision of the most infamous Nazi concentration camp, its gas chambers, and 
crematories. 
</P>
<P>
We, the survivors of the Holocaust, will protest! 
</P>
<P>
RENEE FIRESTONE, Beverly Hills 
</P>
</TEXT>
