<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Officials at the Department of Housing and Urban Development have decided to 
revamp, rather than rescind, the troubled mortgage coinsurance program for 
multifamily housing that resulted in $700 million in defaulted mortgages and 
sparked a criminal investigation into one participant, the Washington Post 
reported. HUD Secretary Jack Kemp's announcement, expected today, will follow a 
four-month review of the program. HUD will create a new Office of Coinsurance 
and set stricter eligibility requirements for lenders who want to do business 
with the government, sources said. 
</P>
