<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
EX-CHAMP DENIES DRUG CHARGES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CINCINNATI 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Former world junior welterweight boxing champion Aaron T. Pryor, 34, has 
pleaded innocent to drug charges, saying a cocaine pipe police found in his car 
belongs to a friend who borrowed the vehicle recently. 
</P>
<P>
Police arrested Pryor late Monday and charged him under a city drug 
paraphernalia ordinance after finding the pipe in the car's seat. Pryor pleaded 
innocent to the charge Tuesday in Hamilton County Municipal Court. 
</P>
<P>
Pryor, who has a career record of 37-1 with 33 knockouts, was world champion 
from 1980 until 1985. Officials took him off the boxing card Jan. 26 after 
doctors said his left eye was too badly injured to let him fight. Before 
undergoing eye surgery in January, Pryor said he had overcome a cocaine 
addiction that crippled comeback attempts in 1986 and 1987. 
</P>
</TEXT>
